09165nam a22012975i 9781614512813DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20132013gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2012043397  a97816145128137 a10.1515/97816145128132doi  a(DE-B1597)207138  a(OCoLC)979743926  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aP115.45b.C87 2013 4aP115.45 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a306.44/600aCurrent Multilingualism :bA New Linguistic Dispensation /ced. by David Singleton, Joshua A. Fishman, Larissa Aronin, Muiris Ó Laoire. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (375 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContributions to the Sociology of Language [CSL] ,x1861-0676 ;v10200tFrontmatter -- tTable of contents -- tIntroduction -- tCurrent multilingualism: A new linguistic dispensation -- tI Language teaching and language learning -- t1 ELF: Central or Atypical Second Language Acquisition? -- t2 Faraway, so close: Trilingualism in the Basque Autonomous Community and Malta from a socio-educational perspective -- t3 Issues in all-Irish education: Strengthening the case for comparative immersion -- t4 Informal bilingual acquisition: Dynamic spaces for language education policy -- tII Social aspects of current multilingualism -- t5 Minority language use in Ireland: The time dimension -- t6 Mapping increasing linguistic diversity in multicultural Europe and abroad -- t7 Multilingual attitudes and attitudes to multilingualism in Croatia -- t8 Emerging and conflicting forces of polyphony in the Berlin speech community after the fall of the Wall: On the social identity of adolescents -- t9 Multilingualism in Morocco and the linguistic features of the Casablanca variety -- t10 Multilingualism in Sweden -- tIII Language Policy -- t11 Language planning for a decimated and often forgotten non-territorial tongue -- t12 Endangered languages and endangered archives in the Russian Federation -- t13 Linguistic quandary in multilingual Malaysia: Socio-political issues, language policy, educational changes -- t14 Managing language diversity in the Irish health services -- t15 Slipping between policy and management: (De)centralised responses to linguistic diversity in Ethiopia and South Africa -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume approaches contemporary multilingualism as a new linguistic dispensation, in urgent need of research-led, reflective scrutiny. The book addresses the emergent global and local patterns of multingual use and acquisition across the world and explores the major trends that characterize today's multilingualism. It is divided into three parts on the basis of the broad themes: education (including multilingual learning in its general, theoretical aspects), sociolinguistic dimensions and language policy. The book's fifteen chapters, written by renowned international experts, discuss a range of issues relating to the quintessential and unique properties of multilingual situations – issues relevant to the challenges faced in different ways by researcher and practitioners alike. All the contributions share a focus on currently operative patterns of interaction between contexts, events and processes.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aMultilingualismxSocial aspects. 0aSecond language acquisition. 0aSociolinguistics. 4aMehrsprachigkeit. 4aSoziolinguistik. 4aSprachplanung. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aGlobalization.  aLanguage Education.  aMultilingualism.  aSociolinguistics.  aSociology of Language.1 aAronin, Larissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAronin